[1] COVID-19 and Tuberculosis
Date: 15 Aug 2020
Source: NCBI [edited]
https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/research/coronavirus/publication/32794460


SARS-CoV-2 is responsible for coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19). The 1st COVID-19 case was detected 10 Mar 2020 in Turkey, and as of 18 May 2020, 148 067 cases have been identified, and 4096 citizens have died.

Tuberculosis (TB) is a worldwide public health concern; incidence of tuberculosis (per 100 000 people) in Turkey was reported at 14.1 in 2018. During the pandemic, COVID-19 has been the main concern in every clinic, and as we discuss here, overlapping respiratory diseases may result in delaying diagnosis and treatment.

Methodology: There were 4605 respiratory samples examined between 23 Mar and 18 May 2020 for COVID-19 and 185 samples for _Mycobacterium tuberculosis_ in our laboratory. The Xpert Ultra assay was performed for the diagnosis of pulmonary tuberculosis; SARS-CoV-2 RNA was determined by real-time PCR (RT-PCR) analysis in combined nasopharyngeal and deep oropharyngeal swabs of suspected cases of COVID-19.

Results: Both of SARS-CoV-2 and _M. tuberculosis_ tests were requested on clinical and radiological grounds in 30 patients. Here, we discuss 2 patients who were both COVID-19 and TB positive. One patient already diagnosed with tuberculosis became COVID-19 positive during hospitalization, and another patient suspected and treated for COVID-19 received a final diagnosis of pulmonary TB and human immunodeficiency virus [HIV] infection.

Conclusions: We want to emphasize that while considering COVID-19 primarily during these pandemic days, we should not forget one of the "great imitators," tuberculosis, within differential diagnoses.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

