Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The number of countries and territories reporting confirmed cases of COVID-19 to WHO remains at 215. In the 24 hours since the last WHO update:

- The Americas region reported 55.0% of the global newly reported cases and 77.6% of newly reported deaths for this 24-hour period, maintaining its dominance as the most severely affected region, having reported more than 11.2 million cases. Brazil reported 37.1% (60 091) of new cases, followed by USA 32.6% (52 799), Colombia 7.0% (11 286), Peru 5.8% (9441), Argentina 4.6% (7498), Mexico 4.5% (7371), and Chile 1.3% (2077).

- The European region reported 9.9% of the global newly reported cases and 3.6% of the newly confirmed deaths globally. Spain reported 18.7% (5479) of the regional newly confirmed cases, followed by Russia 17.2% (5061), France 9.1% (2667), Ukraine 6.3% (1847), Israel 0% (0), the UK 4.9% (1440), Romania 4.8% (1415), Germany 4.8% (1415), Kazakhstan 4.3% (1267), Turkey 4.2% (1226), Poland 2.8% (832), Uzbekistan 2.3% (690), and Netherlands 2.1% (636). While Russia's proportional representation has fallen, its daily absolute count of newly confirmed cases is basically stable; it's the increased reporting from other countries that causes the decrease in representation of Russia.

- The Eastern Mediterranean region reported 4.5% of the global newly reported cases and 3.6% of global newly reported fatalities. Iraq reported 30.0% (4013) of the regional newly reported cases, followed by Iran 18.6% (2501), Saudi Arabia 10.3% (1383), Morocco 9.3% (1306), Kuwait 9.7% (699), Pakistan 5.6% (747), Palestinian Authority 3.9% (531), Lebanon 2.5% (334), Bahrain 2.4% (326), Libya 2.1% (277), and Qatar 1.8% (251). Cases are continuing to increase in Iraq and Morocco. This region remains highly active, with multiple countries still in a relative surge mode.

- The African region reported 3.6% of the global newly reported cases and 3.8% of newly reported fatalities. South Africa reported 58.2% (6275) of the newly reported cases in the region in the past 24 hours, followed by Ethiopia 9.6% (1038), Kenya 5.4% (580), Algeria 4.4% (477), Zambia 3.3% (358), Nigeria 3.1% (329), Ghana 2.0% (216), Cameroon 0% (0), Namibia 1.7% (182), Gabon 1.4% (148), Senegal 1.2% (132), and Madagascar 1.1% (121).

- The Western Pacific region reported 2.8% of the global newly reported cases and 0.44% of global deaths. The Philippines reported 73.8% (6134) of the newly reported cases in the region, followed by Japan 16.4% (1360), Australia 4.6% (385), South Korea 1.9% (166) and Singapore 1.0% (83), China 0.84% (70). The Philippines, Japan, and Australia continue to have elevated transmission, and Viet Nam continues to report cases in the wake of the Da Nang outbreak, 19 reported in the past 24 hours.

- The South East Asia region reported 24.0% of the global newly reported cases and 10.8% of globally reported deaths. India reported 92.0% (65 002) of newly reported cases in the region, followed by Bangladesh 3.9% (2766), Indonesia 3.2% (2307) and Nepal 0.84% (594). India continues to be the driving force of the dominance of this region.

Impression: The overall picture is basically the same. The ordering of the regions has the Americas having the highest disease load and newly confirmed on a daily basis followed by the South East Asia region, then Europe followed by the Eastern Mediterranean, followed by the Africa region, and the Western Pacific region representing the lowest daily caseload of all the regions. While regional proportions may not reflect this, most of the regions have countries with resurgences associated with lifting of restrictions.

Figure 2. The epidemic curve of confirmed COVID-19 cases by date of report and WHO region, 30 Dec 2019 through 15 Aug 2020, at the source URL above is an excellent visual representation of the epidemic as described in the text above. - Mod.UBA]

